<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	tax
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	es
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	In addition, we incurred approximately $35 million of weather-related costs in 2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Compensation and Benefits
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#x2013;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Compensation and benefits include wages, payroll taxes, health and welfare costs, pension costs, other postretirement benefits, and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	incentive costs. In 2016, expenses
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	decreased 8% compared to 2015, driven by lower volume-related costs, productivity gains, and lower training expense.&nbsp;&nbsp;General wage and benefit inflation partially offset these decreases.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	In 2015, lower volume-related costs and second half productivity gains were more than offset by general wage inflation and increased hiring and training expenses related to a larger workforce in the first half of the year.&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Purchased Services and Materials
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#x2013; Expense for purchased services and materials includes the costs of services purchased from outside contractors and other service providers (including equipment maintenance and contract expenses incurred by our subsidiaries for external transportation services); materials used to maintain the Railroad&#x2019;s lines, structures, and equipment; costs of operating facilities jointly used by UPRR and other railroads; transportation and lodging for train crew employees; trucking and contracting costs for intermodal containers; leased automobile maintenance expenses; and tools and supplies. Purchased services and materials decreased 7% compared to 2015 primarily due to lower volume-related costs and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	lower locomotive and freight car repair
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	and maintenance expenses.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;BACKGROUND-COLOR:YELLOW;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Purchased services and materials
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	in 2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	decreased $137 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	compared to 2014 primarily due to lower volume-related costs, including
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	a decrease in external transportation expenses incurred by our logistics subsidiaries.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	&nbsp;Expenses also decreased due to lower locomotive and freight car repair and maintenance expenses.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Fuel
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#x2013; Fuel includes locomotive fuel and gasoline for highway and non-highway vehicles and heavy equipment.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;COLOR:#000000;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Locomotive diesel fuel prices, which
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;COLOR:#000000;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	averaged
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$1.48 per gallon (including taxes and transportation costs) in 2016, compared to $1.84
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	per gallon in 2015, reduced
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	expenses $347 million. In addition, fuel costs were lower as gross-ton miles decreased 8%. The fuel consumption rate (c-rate), computed as gallons of fuel consumed divided by gross ton-miles in thousands, improved 1% compared
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	to 2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;BORDER-TOP:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;BORDER-TOP:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
</P>

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;COLOR:#000000;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Locomotive diesel fuel prices, which

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;COLOR:#000000;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	averaged
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$1.84 per gallon (including taxes and transportation costs) in 2015, compared to $2.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	97 per gallon in 2014, reduced
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	expenses $1.2 billion
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	in 2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	. In addition, fuel costs
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	in 2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	were lower as gross-ton miles decreased 9%. The fuel consumption rate (c-rate), computed as gallons of fuel consumed divided by gross ton-miles in thousands, increased 1%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	in 2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	compared to 2014. Decreases in heavier, more fuel-efficient shipments,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	decreased
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	gross-ton mile
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	s
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	increased the c-
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	rate.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Depreciation
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#x2013; The majority of depreciation relates to road property, including rail, ties, ballast, and other track material.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	A larger
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	depreciable asset base, reflecting higher capital spending in recent years,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	increased
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	depreciation expense in 2016 compared to 2015. This
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	increase
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	was partially offset by our recent depreciation studies that resulted in lower depreciation rates for some asset classes.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	A higher depreciable asset base, reflecting higher capital spending in recent years, increased depreciation expense in 2015 compared to 2014. This increase was partially offset by our recent depreciation studies that resulted in lower depreciation rates for some asset classes.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;

	Equipment and Other Rents
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#x2013; Equipment and other rents expense primarily includes rental expense that the Railroad pays for freight cars owned by other railroads or private companies; freight car, intermodal, and locomotive leases; and office and other rent
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	expenses
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Equipment and other rents expense
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	decreased
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;$
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	93
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	million compared to 2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	as lower
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	volume levels
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	drove a r
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	educ
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	tion in car
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	hire
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	locomotive lease expense
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	s
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	.

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Other
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#x2013; Other expenses include state and local taxes, freight, equipment and property damage, utilities, insurance, personal injury, environmental, employee travel, telephone and cellular, computer software, bad debt, and other general expenses
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Other expenses
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	increased
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	8%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	in 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	compared to 2015 as a result of higher environmental costs, state and local taxes, bad debt expense (customer bankruptcy), and the write-off of certain in-progress capit
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	al projects that were cancelled
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;These cost increases were partially offset by lower
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	expenses for damaged
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	freight, property
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	equipment
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	not owned by the Company
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.
</FONT>

	were offset by lower costs in other areas

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">

	Other
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	income decreased in
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2016 compared to 2015 primarily due
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	to

	&nbsp;

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	large real estate transactions:
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	a $113 million gain from a real estate sale in 2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, partially offset by $67 million of gains from two real estate sales in 2016.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	primarily due to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	a $113 million gain from a real estate sale in the second quarter of 2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, partially offset by a gain from the sale of a permanent easement in 2014
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.&nbsp;
</FONT>

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	compared to 4.8% in 2015.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	billion in 2015 from $10.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	7
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	billion in 2014, partially offset by the impact of a lower effective interest rate of

	Income Taxes
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	37.4%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	compared to 37.7% in 2015.
</FONT>

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">

</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Average Train Speed
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#x2013; &nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Average train speed is calculated by dividing train miles by hours operated on our main lines
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	between terminals.&nbsp;&nbsp;Average train speed, as reported to the Association of American Railroads,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	improved
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	5
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	% in
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2016 compared to 2015.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Velocity gains resulted from lower volumes, improved network fluidity and a strong resource position.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Average train speed
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	improved 6% in 2015 compared to 2014.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Velocity gains resulted from lower volumes, improved network fluidity and a strong resource position. More favorable weather conditions in the first quarter of 2015 also contributed to the improvement in our average train speed.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Average Terminal Dwell Time
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#x2013; Average terminal dwell time is the average time that a rail car spends at our terminals. Lower average terminal dwell time improves asset utilization and service.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Average terminal dwell
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	time improved 4%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	in 2016 compared to 2015, reflecting
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	the impact of lower volume and improved network operations.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Average terminal dwell time improved 3% in 2015 compared to 2014, reflecting
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	the impact of lower volume and improved network operations.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Gross and Revenue Ton-Miles
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#x2013; Gross ton-miles are calculated by multiplying the weight of loaded and empty freight cars by the number of miles hauled. Revenue ton-miles are calculated by multiplying the weight
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	of freight by the number of tariff miles.&nbsp;&nbsp;Gross ton-miles and revenue ton-miles decreased
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	8%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	9
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	%, respectively in 2016 compared to 2015, resulting from a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	7%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	decrease in
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	carloads.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Changes in commodity mix drove the variances in year-over-year declines between gross
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	ton-miles, revenue ton-miles and carloads.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Gross ton-miles and revenue ton-miles decreased 9% and 12%, respectively in 2015 compared to 2014, resulting from a 6% decrease in
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	carloads.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Changes in commodity mix
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	drove
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	the variances in year-over-year declines between gross ton-miles, revenue ton-miles and carloads.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Operating Ratio
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#x2013; Operating ratio is our operating expenses reflected as a percentage of operating revenue
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our operating
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	ratio increased
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	0.4
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	points to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	63.5%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	in 2016 compared to 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;C
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	ore pric
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	e improvements
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, network efficiencies, and productivity gains were more than offset by the impact of lower volume, inflation, and other costs.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Our operating ratio improved 0.4 points to a new record low of 63.1% in 2015 compared to 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;C
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	ore pricing gains, the impact of lower fuel prices, resource realignments,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	network efficiencies
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and productivity gains
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	more than
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	offset the impact of lower volume and inflation.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
</P>

<FONT SIZE="1">

</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:RIGHT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Employees
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#x2013; Employee
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	levels
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	decreased
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	10%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	in
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2016 compared to 2015,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	driven by lower volume levels, productivity gains, a smaller capital workforce, and fewer transportation employees in training.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Employee levels
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	increased 1% in 2015 compared to 2014,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	driven
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	by more employees in training and an increase in capital project
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	work. More employees were in training as a result of the number of transportation employees hired during the last half of 2014 and early 2015 to handle expected volume increases, and who continued receiving training in 2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, most of which occurred in the first nine months of the year.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
</EFX_RESULTS_OF_OPERATIONS>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	ROIC is considered a non-GAAP financial measure by SEC Regulation G and Item 10 of SEC Regulation S-K, and may not be defined and calculated by other companies in the same manner. We believe this measure is important to management and investors in evaluating the efficiency and effectiveness of our long-term capital investments.&nbsp;&nbsp;In addition, we currently use ROIC as a performance criteria in determining certain elements of equity compensation for our executives. ROIC should be considered in addition to, rather than as a substitute for, other information provided in accordance with GAAP. The most comparable GAAP measure is Return on Average Common Shareholders&#x2019; Equity. The tables above provide reconciliations from return on average common shareholders&#x2019; equity to ROIC. Our 2016 ROIC
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	decreased
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	1.6 points compared to 2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, primarily as a result
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	of lower earnings and a higher invested capital base.
</FONT>
</P>

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Adjusted debt to capital is a non-GAAP financial measure under SEC Regulation G and Item 10 of SEC Regulation S-K, and may not be defined and calculated by other companies in the same manner. We believe this measure is important to management and investors in evaluating the total amount of leverage in our capital structure, including off-balance sheet lease obligations, which we generally incur in connection with financing the acquisition of locomotives and freight cars and certain facilities.&nbsp;&nbsp;Operating leases were discounted
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	using 4.7%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and 4.8% at
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	December 31, 2016, and 2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, respectively. The discount rate reflects our effective interest rate. We monitor the ratio of adjusted debt to capital as we manage our capital structure to balance cost-effective and efficient access to the capital markets with our overall cost of capital. Adjusted debt to capital should be considered in addition to, rather than as a substitute for, debt to capital. The tables above provide reconciliations from debt to capital to adjusted debt to capital. Our
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	December 31, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	debt to capital
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	ratios
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	increased
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	as a result of a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	n
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$800 m
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	illion
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	increase
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	in debt from
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	December 31, 2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.
</FONT>

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	LIQUIDITY AND CAPITAL RESOURCES
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	As of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	December 31, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, our principal sources of liquidity included cash, cash equivalents, our receivables securitization facility, and our revolving credit facility, as well as the availability of commercial
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	paper and other sources of financing through the capital markets.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	We had
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$1.7
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	billion of committed credit available under our credit facility, with no borrowings outstanding as of December 31,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	. We did not make any borrowings under this facility during 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	. The value of the outstanding undivided interest held by investors under the $650 million capacity receivables securiti
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	zation facility was $0
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	as
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	December 31, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	. Our access to this receivables securitization facility may be reduced or restricted if our bond ratings fall to certain levels below investment grade. If our bond rating were to deteriorate, it could have an adverse impact on our liquidity. Access to commercial paper as well as other capital market financings is dependent on market conditions. Deterioration of our operating results or financial condition due to internal or external factors could negatively impact our ability to access capital markets as a source of liquidity. Access to liquidity through the capital markets is also dependent on our financial stability. We expect that we will continue to have access to liquidity through any or all of the following sources or activities: (i) increasing the size or utilization of our receivables securitization, (ii) issuing commercial paper, (iii) entering into bank loans, outside of our revolving credit facility, or (iv) issuing bonds or other debt securities to public or private investors based on our assessment of the current condition of the credit markets. The
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Company&#x2019;s $1.7 billion revolving credit facility is
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	intended to support the issuance of commercial paper by UPC and also serves as an emergency source of liquidity. The Company currently does not intend to make any borrowings under this facility.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	At
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	December 31, 2016,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	we had a working capital deficit, which does not indicate a lack of liquidity.&nbsp;&nbsp;We maintain adequate resources and, when necessary, have adequate access to capital markets to meet any foreseeable cash requirements, in addition to sufficient financial capacity to satisfy our current liabilities.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	The decrease at 2016 year-end was primarily due to a decrease in other current assets related to a tax receivable for the late extension of bonus depreciation at December 31, 2015, along with an increase at December 31, 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	in accounts payable and upcoming debt maturities.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	At December 31,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, we had a working capital surplus.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 1PT">

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Operating Activities
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Cash provided by opera
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	ting activities increased in 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	compared to 201
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	5.&nbsp;&nbsp;The timing of tax payments primarily related to bonus depreciation and changes in working capital more than offset lower net income.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Cash provided by operating activities decreased in 2015 compared to 2014 due to lower net income and changes in working capital, partially offset by the timing of tax payments.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	In December of 2014,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	Congress extended 50% bonus depreciation for 2014;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	however
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	the related benefit was realized in 2015, rather than 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;Similarly, in December of 2015, Congress extended bonus depreciation through 2019, which delayed the benefit of 2015 bonus depreciation into 2016.&nbsp;&nbsp;Bonus depreciation will be at a rate of 50% for 2016 and 2017, 40% for 2018 and 30% for 2019.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Investing Activities
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Lower capital investments, partially offset by short-term investment purchases, decreased cash used in investing activities in 2016 compared to 2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">

	&nbsp;

	which we exercised due to favorable economic terms and market conditions,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	drove
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	the increase in cash used in investing activities in 2015 compared to 2014
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	. &nbsp;

	10,791&nbsp;

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;COLOR:#000000;">
	Capital Plan
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	&#x2013;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	In 2017, we expect our capital plan to be
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	approximately $
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	3
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	1
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	billion
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	, which may be revised if business conditions or the regulatory environment affect our ability to generate sufficient returns on
</FONT>
</P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:RIGHT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	35
</FONT>
</P>
</DIV>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<P STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage37"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	these investments
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;While asset replacements will fluctuate as part of our renewal strategy, we expect to use 65% to 75% of our capital investments to renew and improve existing capital assets.&nbsp;&nbsp;We will continue to invest in our network and terminals where appropriate, balancing terminal capacity with mainline capacity.&nbsp;&nbsp;Significant investments in technology improvements are planned, including approximately $300 million for PTC.&nbsp;&nbsp;We
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	also
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	will continue commercial investments in rail facilit
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	ies and equipment, including approximately 60
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	locomotives
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	intermodal containers and chassis, and freight cars
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	We expect to fund our 2017 cash capital plan by using some or all of the following: cash generated from operations, proceeds from the sale or lease of various operating and non-operating properties, proceeds from the issuance of long-term debt, and cash on hand. Our annual capital plan is a critical component of our long-term strategic plan. We expect our plan will enhance the long-term value of the Company for our shareholders by providing sufficient resources to (i) replace and improve our existing track infrastructure to provide safe and fluid operations, (ii) increase network efficiency by adding or improving facilities and track, and (iii) make investments that meet customer demand and take advantage of opportunities for long-term growth.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Financing Activities
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Cash used in financing activities increased in 2016 compared to 2015.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	An increase of $457 million in debt repaid and a decrease of $1,345 million in debt issued more than offset a decrease of $465 million in dividends paid. The
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	decrease in dividends paid was a result of adjusting the dividend payable dates in 2015 to align with the timing of the quarterly dividend declaration and payment dates within the same quarter. Aligning the quarterly dividend declaration and payment resulted in two payments in the first quarter of 2015: the fourth quarter 2014 dividend of $438 million, which was paid on January 2, 2015, as well as the first quarter 2015 dividend of $484 million, which was paid on March 30, 2015. The second quarter 2015 dividend of $479 million was paid on June 30, 2015, the third quarter 2015 dividend of $476 million was paid on September 30, 2015, and the fourth quarter 2015 dividend of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	$467
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	million was paid on December 31, 2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Cash used in financing activities increased in 2015 compared to 2014.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	An increase of $712 million in dividends paid
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	$240 million for the repurchase of shares under our common stock repurchase program more than offset an increase of $740 million in debt issued and a decrease of $154 million in debt repaid. The higher
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	dividend payments primarily were a result of adjusting the dividend payable dates to align with the timing of the quarterly dividend declaration and payment within the same quarter as mentioned above.&nbsp;&nbsp;Higher dividends per share also contributed to the increase in dividends paid.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	See Note 15 of the Consolidated Financial Statements for a description of all our outstanding financing arrangements and significant new borrowings.&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Ratio of Earnings to Fixed Charges
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	For each of the years ended December 31, 2016, 2015, and 2014, our ratio of earnings to fixed charges was
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	9.6,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	11.6, and 13.5, respectively. The ratio of earnings to fixed charges was computed on a consolidated basis. Earnings represent income from continuing operations, less equity earnings net of distributions, plus fixed charges and income taxes. Fixed charges represent interest charges, amortization of debt discount, and the estimated amount representing the interest portion of rental charges.&nbsp;&nbsp;(See Exhibit 12 to this report for the calculation of the ratio of earnings to fixed charges.)
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;

</FONT>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">

	&#xFEFF;

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#x2013; Our revolving credit facility includes a debt-to-net worth covenant (discussed in the Credit Facilities section above) that, under certain circumstances, restricts the payment of cash dividends to our shareholders. The amount of retained earnings available for dividends was
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$12.4
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	billion and $13.6 billion at
</FONT>

	, respectively.

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	On November 17, 2016, our Board of Directors approved the early renewal of the share repurchase program, authorizing the repurchase of up to 120 million shares of our common stock by December 31, 2020. The new authorization was effective January 1, 2017, and replaces the previous authorization, which expired on Decem
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	ber 31, 2016.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Management's assessments of market conditions and other pertinent facts guide the timing and volume of all repurchases.&nbsp;&nbsp;We expect to fund any share repurchases under this program through cash generated from operations, the sale or lease of various operating and non-operating properties, debt issuances, and cash on hand.&nbsp;&nbsp;Repurchased shares are recorded in treasury stock at cost, which includes any applicable commissions and fees.
</FONT>
</P>

	&#xFEFF;

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	As described in the notes to the Consolidated Financial Statements and as referenced in the tables below, we have contractual obligations and commercial commitments that may affect our financial condition. Based on our assessment of the underlying provisions and circumstances of our contractual obligations and commercial commitments, including material sources of off-balance sheet and structured finance arrangements, other than the risks that we and other similarly situated companies face with respect to the condition of the capital markets (as described in Item 1A of Part II of this report),&nbsp;&nbsp;there is no known trend, demand, commitment, event, or uncertainty that is reasonably likely to occur that would have a material adverse effect on our consolidated results of operations, financial condition, or liquidity. In addition, our commercial obligations, financings, and commitments are customary transactions that are similar to those of other comparable corporations, particularly within the transportation industry.

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	million and $53 million in guarantees. T
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	he fair value of these obligations as of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	both
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	December 31, 2016, and 2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	, was
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	$0
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	. We entered into these contingent guarantees in the normal course of business, and they include guaranteed obligations related to our affiliated operations. The final guarantee expires in
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	2022.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	We are not aware of any existing event of default that would require us to satisfy these guarantees. We do not expect that these guarantees will have a material adverse effect on our consolidated financial condition, results of operations, or liquidity.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;COLOR:#000000;">
	OTHER MATTERS
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;COLOR:#000000;">
	Labor Agreements
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	&#x2013; &nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	Approximately 84% of our 42,919 full-time-equivalent employees are represented by 14 major rail unions. On January 1, 2015, current labor agreements became subject to modification and we began the current round of negotiations with the unions. Existing agreements remain in effect until new agreements
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	are reached or the Railway Labor Act&#x2019;s (RLA) procedures (which include mediation, cooling-off periods, and the possibility of Presidential Emergency Boards and Congressional intervention) are exhausted.&nbsp;&nbsp;The railroad industry is currently in mediation with all bargaining coalitions.&nbsp;&nbsp;Under the Railway Labor Act, the National Mediation Board controls timing and location of mediation conferences and when to terminate mediation, moving the parties to the next stages of the RLA process.&nbsp;&nbsp;Contract negotiations historically continue for an extended period of time and we rarely experience work stoppages while negotiations are pending
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
</P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>

<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">

	&nbsp;

<A NAME="eolPage40"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Inflation
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#x2013; Long periods of inflation significantly increase asset replacement costs for capital-intensive companies. As a result, assuming that we replace all operating assets at current price levels, depreciation charges (on an inflation-adjusted basis) would be substantially greater than historically reported amounts.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Sensitivity Analyses
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#x2013; The sensitivity analyses that follow illustrate the economic effect that hypothetical changes in interest rates could have on our results of operations and financial condition. These hypothetical changes do not consider other factors that could impact actual results.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	At December 31, 2016, we had variable-rate debt representing approximately 0.7% of our total debt. If variable interest rates average one percentage point higher in 2017 than our December 31, 2016 variable rate, which was approximately 1.7%, our interest expense would increase by approximately $1 million. This amount was determined by considering the impact of the hypothetical interest rate on the balances of our variable-rate debt at December 31, 2016.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Market risk for fixed-rate debt is estimated as the potential increase in fair value resulting from a hypothetical one percentage point decrease in interest rates as of December 31, 2016, and amounts to an increase of approximately $1.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	9
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	billion to the fair value of our debt at December 31, 2016. We estimated the fair values of our fixed-rate debt by considering the impact of the hypothetical interest rates on quoted market prices and current borrowing rates.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;BACKGROUND-COLOR:YELLOW;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Accounting Pronouncements
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#x2013; See Note 3 to the Consolidated Financial Statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;BACKGROUND-COLOR:YELLOW;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Asserted and Unasserted Claims
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#x2013; Various claims and lawsuits are pending against us and certain of our subsidiaries. We cannot fully determine the effect of all asserted and unasserted claims on our consolidated results of operations, financial condition, or liquidity. To the extent possible, we have recorded a liability where asserted and unasserted claims are considered probable and where such claims can be reasonably estimated. We do not expect that any known lawsuits, claims, environmental costs, commitments, contingent liabilities, or guarantees will have a material adverse effect on our consolidated results of operations, financial condition, or liquidity after taking into account liabilities and insurance recoveries previously recorded for these matters.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Indemnities
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#x2013; Our maximum potential exposure under indemnification arrangements, including certain tax indemnifications, can range from a specified dollar amount to an unlimited amount, depending on the nature of the transactions and the agreements. Due to uncertainty as to whether claims will be made or how they will be resolved, we cannot reasonably determine the probability of an adverse claim or reasonably estimate any adverse liability or the total maximum exposure under these indemnification arrangements. We do not have any reason to believe that we will be required to make any material payments under these indemnity provisions.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Climate Change
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#x2013; Although climate change could have an adverse impact on our operations and financial performance in the future (see Risk Factors under Item 1A of this report), we are currently unable to predict the manner or severity of such impact. However, we continue to take steps and explore opportunities to reduce the impact of our operations on the environment, including investments in new technologies, using training programs to reduce fuel consumption, and changing our operations to increase fuel efficiency.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	CR
</FONT>
<A NAME="UNP-20161231X10K_HTM_CRITICALACCOUNTINGPOLICIES">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	ITICAL ACCOUNTING POLICIES
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Our Consolidated Financial Statements have been prepared in accordance with GAAP. The preparation of these financial statements requires estimation and judgment that affect the reported amounts of revenues, expenses, assets, and liabilities. We base our estimates on historical experience and on various other assumptions that we believe are reasonable under the circumstances, the results of which form the basis for making judgments about the carrying values of assets and liabilities that are not readily apparent from other sources. The following critical accounting policies are a subset of our significant accounting policies described in Note 2 to the Financial Statements and Supplementary Data, Item 8. These critical accounting policies affect significant areas of our financial statements and involve judgment and estimates. If these estimates differ significantly from actual results, the impact on our Consolidated Financial Statements may be material.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Personal Injury
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#x2013; The cost of personal injuries to employees and others related to our activities is charged to expense based on estimates of the ultimate cost and number of incidents each year. We use an actuarial analysis to measure the expense and liability, including unasserted claims. The Federal
</FONT>
</P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:RIGHT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	39
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS">
	&nbsp;

<A NAME="eolPage41"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Employers&#x2019; Liability Act (FELA) governs compensation for work-related accidents. Under FELA, damages are assessed based on a finding of fault through litigation or out-of-court settlements. We offer a comprehensive variety of services and rehabilitation programs for employees who are injured at work.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Our personal injury liability is not discounted to present value due to the uncertainty surrounding the timing of future payments. Approximately
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	94% of the recorded liability is related to asserted claims and approximately 6% is related to unasserted claims at December 31, 2016. Because of the uncertainty surrounding the ultimate
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	outcome of personal injury claims, it is reasonably possible that future costs to settle these claims may range from
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	approximately $290 million to $317
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million. We record an accrual at the low end of the range as no amount of loss within the range is more probable than any other.&nbsp;&nbsp;Estimates can vary over time due to evolving trends in litigation.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Asbestos
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#x2013; We are a defendant in a number of lawsuits in which current and former employees and other parties allege exposure to asbestos. We assess our potential liability using a statistical analysis of resolution costs for asbestos-related claims.&nbsp;&nbsp;This liability is updated annually and excludes future defense and processing costs. The liability for resolving both asserted and unasserted claims was based on the following assumptions:
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	Our liability for asbestos-related
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	claims is not discounted to present value due to the uncertainty surrounding the timing of future payments. Approximately 20% of the recorded liability related to asserted claims and approximately 80% related to unasserted claims at December 31, 2016.&nbsp;&nbsp;Because of the uncertainty surrounding the ultimate outcome
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	of asbestos-
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	related claims, it is reasonably possible that future costs to settle these claims may range from approximately $111 million to $118 million.&nbsp;&nbsp;We record an accrual at the low end of the range as no amount of loss within the range is more
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	probable than any other.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">

</FONT>

<P STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS">
	&nbsp;

<A NAME="eolPage42"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Our asbestos-related liability activity was as follows:

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	In conjunction with the liability update performed in 2016, we also reassessed our estimated insurance recoveries. We have recognized an asset for estimated insurance recoveries at
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	December 31, 2016, and 2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;The amounts recorded for asbestos-related liabilities and related insurance recoveries were based on currently known facts. However, future events, such as the number of new claims filed each year, average settlement costs, and insurance coverage issues, could cause the actual costs and insurance recoveries to be higher or lower than the projected amounts. Estimates also may vary in the future if strategies, activities, and outcomes of asbestos litigation materially change; federal and state laws governing asbestos litigation increase or decrease the probability or amount of compensation of claimants; and there are material changes with respect to payments made to claimants by other defendants.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Environmental Costs
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#x2013; We are subject to federal, state, and local environmental laws and regulations. We have
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	identified 292
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	sites at which we are or
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	may be liable for remediation costs associated with alleged contamination or for violations of environmental requirements. This includes 33 sites that are the subject of actions taken by the U.S. government, 21 of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	which are currently on the Superfund National Priorities List. Certain federal legislation imposes joint and several liability for the remediation of identified sites; consequently, our ultimate environmental liability may include costs relating to activities of other parties, in addition to costs relating to our own activities at each site.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	When we identify an environmental issue with respect to property owned, leased, or otherwise used in our business, we perform, with assistance of our consultants, environmental assessments on the property. We expense the cost of the assessments as incurred. We accrue the cost of remediation where our obligation is probable and such costs can be reasonably estimated. Our environmental liability is not discounted to present value due to the uncertainty surrounding the timing of future payments.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Our environmental liability activity was as follows:
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;FONT-SIZE: 1PT">
